tr.td: Title: Office Visit Comprehensive
Author: Varhan MD, Kral

1. Fracture of lateral malleolus of right ankle S82.61XA
2. Displaced fracture of fifth metatarsal bone, right foot, initial encounter for closed fracture S92.351A
Patient missed a step and twisted her right foot and ankle couple days ago. Initially she did not think much of it and she continued to walk but she had persistent right foot and ankle pain.X-rays in the emergency department revealed fracture of her foot and ankle and she was placed in a posterior splint.She had stroke in the past but she did not have any residual motor weakness.She is on Plavix because of her previous stroke.I reviewed her right foot and ankle x-rays.She has a fracture of lateral malleolus distally and comminuted and slightly displaced fracture of the base of her fifth Metatarsal.We discussed the operative and nonoperative options available.The nonoperative option would involve placing her in a walking boot and keeping her nonweightbearing 6 weeks to start with up to 3 months and following her closely with repeated x-rays.Operative option would involve placing a small plate and intramedullary screw in the distal fibula and placing an intramedullary screw into the fifth metatarsal.The rationale for the operative fixation involves stabilization of the fracture and allowing her to weight-bear early.Especially the base of the fifth metatarsal fracture involves an area with decreased blood supply and the pill of the peroneus tendon is in the direction of distraction at the fracture site. The risks of the surgery include but not limited to infection, neurovascular injury, nonunion, malunion, and hardware problems.After discussing the pros and cons of each option she decided to go ahead with surgical treatment. Accordingly we are booking her surgery to be done early next week. She will stop her Plavix this weekend.

NP | ER FOLLOW UP RIGHT FOOT FRACTURE
Additional Information
Patient states she is having pain. Patient states MOI was falling off her steps.

Patient presents in office this date as an ER follow up for evaluation of right foot. She reports she was going down the steps when she missed the last step and twisted her right ankle. She had increased pain with weight bearing. She presents in well fitting splint from the ER.

Doctor's Attestation for Scribe: The documentation recorded by the scribe accurately reflects the service I personally performed and the decisions made by me, Kral Varhan

Present in room for exam: Yes
Scribe Attestation: Documentation prepared by Laura Foerg, acting as medical Scribe for Dr. Varhan.
Assessment/Plan
1. Fracture of lateral malleolus of right ankle S82.61XA
2. Displaced fracture of fifth metatarsal bone, right foot, initial encounter for closed fracture S92.351A
Patient missed a step and twisted her right foot and ankle couple days ago. Initially she did not think much of it and she continued to walk but she had persistent right foot and ankle pain.X-rays in the emergency department revealed fracture of her foot and ankle and she was placed in a posterior splint.She had stroke in the past but she did not have any residual motor weakness.She is on Plavix because of her previous stroke.I reviewed her right foot and ankle x-rays.She has a fracture of lateral malleolus distally and comminuted and slightly displaced fracture of the base of her fifth Metatarsal.We discussed the operative and nonoperative options available.The nonoperative option would involve placing her in a walking boot and keeping her nonweightbearing 6 weeks to start with up to 3 months and following her closely with repeated x-rays.Operative option would involve placing a small plate and intramedullary screw in the distal fibula and placing an intramedullary screw into the fifth metatarsal.The rationale for the operative fixation involves stabilization of the fracture and allowing her to weight-bear early.Especially the base of the fifth metatarsal fracture involves an area with decreased blood supply and the pill of the peroneus tendon is in the direction of distraction at the fracture site. The risks of the surgery include but not limited to infection, neurovascular injury, nonunion, malunion, and hardware problems.After discussing the pros and cons of each option she decided to go ahead with surgical treatment. Accordingly we are booking her surgery to be done early next week. She will stop her Plavix this weekend.
